This is Wednesday, June the 13th, and I am in the Kleberg building and have the honor and pleasure of interviewing Dr. Harry Kunkel, a splendid colleague and distinguished faculty member and administrator here, about his experience, experiences, after he came back following his student days here.
Harry, after you graduated from A&M, briefly describe what happened to you, your experiences between graduation and when you came back here as an employee.
We immediately volunteered for immediate induction and went down to Houston two days after we graduated.
I didn't even go home.
And graduation was when, what year?
January 25th or something of that sort.
And we all became in the Army and within a week we got notice that we had to report for duty and those who were in the artillery ended up at Fort Sill, Oklahoma in the Officer Candidate School.
And there were a group of Aggies in that officer candidate school, and we all went, most of us went through together and were commissioned in May 1943 and went from there to various places.
Where'd you go?
I went to the 65th Division in Camp Shelby, Mississippi and joined the situation.
But that was the first of my problems.
I was carrying a man piggyback and exercise and I broke a leg and spent essentially a whole year in medical situation in the Army and recovery.
After that, I was a casual.
That meant I was unassigned to any unit particularly.
And most of the time was in Jackson, Mississippi and Fort Sill, Oklahoma.
And then after that, I, as a casual, was sent to the Pacific
I was given a, I'd been in long enough to get an automatic promotion to first lieutenant because the time and grade was there.
Eventually spent 50, well, went across the Pacific in a troop ship.
I was in command of 269 black African Americans, which was an interesting observation, just for thinking.
Mostly from what part of the country?
They were all over the country.
I didn't specifically.
Became friends with some of them.
Infantry?
Well, they went into various places.
I only ran into one or two after later on.

Then I was a casual in the Philippines right after Manila was taken and got to go out and see Corregidor with all the Japanese skulls still lying around and the place completely scorched with flames and things of the sort.
And from that point I was assigned to the Americal Division
This was the only unnumbered division in the United States Army.
Why was it unnumbered?
Well, it started largely with a group of units from the National Guard.
I see.
And they assembled in New Caledonia, and so they called it Americans in New Caledonia, a very Cal division.
The patch was the Southern Cross, blue on blue.
I stayed with them, and one evening we were in Cebu.
We had an officer's class, and we walked out of the officer's class and down in the enlistment situation, all heck was breaking loose.
Japan had surrendered.
So we went in as part of the Army of Occupation.
And the units that I transferred to went all the way up to the northern end of Honshu, across Honshu in several units, including the 1st Cavalry Division.
How did the civilian population of Japan react to you Americans?
When we first drove through the streets of Oklahoma, they hid.
They were out of sight.
And I boldly sat up in the back of a jeep and looked around and looked for them and things of the sort.
So no one said anything, did, threw anything?
No, didn't do anything.
And we generally began to get closer and you'd go in for a conference and the first thing you would do would hear the hissing sound, which is their greeting.
Oh, that's a positive.
Yes.
Okay.
Yeah, it's a greeting that the Japanese used at that particular time.
Let's back up just a second.
Do you remember where the circumstances under which you and your colleagues heard about the first A-bomb being dropped?
Well, we were in Cebu Island.
What was the reaction?
I think it was pretty quiet.
Well, okay, they deserved it.
We were fighting the battle.
Our unit was destined to go in in D-4.
That's four days before the main invasion.
We were destined to go into Kyoto as a diversionary end of things while the major attack was going to be in and around Honshu.
Tokyo, I suspect, in a particular area.
We traveled from Cebu to Yokohama, and we were in the Tokyo Bay at the same time the Japanese were on Missouri surrendering.
But we didn't see it.
Did that make any change in the civilian population in Japan, that ceremony?
I suspect it did.
Of course, I didn't know them.
They were generally, you expected the Japanese to be vicious kinds of people in their fighting, and they were pretty calm.
and accepted us.
We had no particular difficulty.
We generally walked around with a pistol in our holster.
All right, then you're in the occupation force, and then what after that?
Well, I came home and was released in June.
Of 46.
And I immediately came back to Texas A&M and got an assistantship
in animal husbandry with going for the degree of animal nutrition.
And what was your career goal at that point?
Were you hoping to be a faculty member?
I was going to become a faculty member.
I just at that point I had run in my undergraduate career I had run across Paul Pearson who I
treasured, and I made contact with him immediately after it, and he offered me an assistantship sight unseen, I guess, or he knew me.
What did that assistantship include?
Oh, it included the opportunity to do research and
seventy-five dollars a month.
Now I was rich because you see the yeah the GI Bill at the GI Bill and the
with the $75 in assistantship.
That added up to 300 bucks a month, and 300 bucks a month was something in those days.
And you began that when?
In September 1946.
Oh, so pretty soon after you got out.
It was immediately.
I was offered several jobs in my hometown, but I decided I was going to go back.
And where did you live here that first fall?
I lived in the dormitory, one of the newer dormitories over here.
Was everything filled up in the fall of 46?
Yes.
And you old veterans, I'll bet, dominated the campus numerically.
We dominated the campus because the young people hadn't come back and the military was small at that particular point.
Military component was small.
What were your duties as assistant other than to do research?
That was it.
I had a research assistantship.
Were you to work on his project, or could you do your own?
Well, basically it was his project.
He had a grant to work on magnesium, the nutrition of magnesium.
And so I began to essentially work in that particular area.
And then in February, January 1948,
with a master's degree in hand, I went up to Cornell where I had an assistantship, $125 there a month.
And the GI Bill.
And the GI Bill.
And what was your research topic up there?
Well, there I was pretty much on my own, which actually I did a subject on linoleic acid and its oxidation.
Linoleic.
Linoleic acid.
Spell that.

l-i-n-o-l-e-i-c linoleic acid it's an 18 carbon two double bond fatty acid with the two double bonds interrupted with a methylene group ch group two ch2 group and it becomes and it's an unstable situation and can be easily oxidized and
I worked with trying to isolate an enzyme called lipoxidase and work with colors such as Bixen to see whether or not it could operate on that particular situation.
And what varieties of animals did this mix?
None.
This wasn't bovine?
No, it wasn't bovine or animals.
How did Cornell compare in your experiences there to what you had known here at A&M?
Describe Cornell at that era.
Well, Cornell was an established institution.
Texas A&M, from a graduate standpoint, was fairly new, was extremely new at that particular point and young.
Well, you know, at the time I graduated, the first, second, and third PhDs graduated in 1943.
So you can imagine 1946, they didn't have many PhDs graduating.
And so it wasn't until about 1948, 49, 50 that they began to turn out PhDs at this institution.
Are you saying the first PhDs in the institution?
in the institution.
Oh, not just in animal science.
No, no.
The second and third PhDs at Texas A&M College were graduated in 1943, the same time I got my baccalaureate degree.
And one of them was R.E.
Patterson.
The other was Van Little.
who were the history of Texas A&M was involved in.
Up at Cornell, how well prepared did you find yourself with your A&M background compared to the other graduate students you encountered?
No, I had no problem.
I was prepared.
Went there with a great deal of confidence.
My major professor was James B. Sumner, S-U-M-N-E-R, who won the Nobel Prize in 1946.
And I really wished that I had been able to work closer with him, but somehow I was a person that went off on my own and probably would have had a better treatment as far as this is concerned.
My committee consisted of James, Dr. Sumner, Dr. Jack Loosley, an animal husbandry, I guess, animal nutrition then, and Dr. H.H.
Dukes, who is a legendary physiologist in veterinary medicine.
How big was the doctoral program in the department?
I guess they had 20 or so students as far as the doctoral program was concerned.
As they would define it, was it in biochemistry or animal science?
It was biochemistry.
I took a degree in biochemistry.
And you finished up when?
I finished up in 1950.
And did you stay up there until then?

I stayed up there till then and in June 1950 I hauled back down to Texas because I had a post-doctorate appointment at the University of Wisconsin Department of Biochemistry and I went back on up and June the 1st 1946 I became a member of the faculty as an instructor
in the Department of Biochemistry, University of Wisconsin.
Now you said 46, you meant 50?
Yeah, 1950.
And how did Wisconsin compare with Cornell and here?

As far as biochemistry was concerned, you have to recognize that the Department of Biochemistry in the latter part of the 1950s was turning out one-third of the PhDs in biochemistry in the United States.
Wisconsin?
Wisconsin, I'm sorry.
Wow.
And I, of course, had my doctorate there and was on the staff.
And they did a lot of inbreeding as far as that's concerned.
As a matter of fact, they said, what year did you get your PhD at Wisconsin?
I didn't do that.
And how did you get on the faculty here?
But I had a good time.
And then one cold day, temperature dropped to 42 below zero.
I got a call from Texas A&M University offering me a job that September, and I said, I'll take it.
And you had not sought it?
There was no- Well, I was nominated, and it was indicated, yes, I would be interested in the job.
But they had, rather than, you see, I have a strange situation.
I have never taken a job for which I interviewed.
I've never interviewed for the job that I've taken.
And you were to begin then here when?
September 1951.
Okay, now this is the only money question we're going to ask about pay at Texas A&M.
What was your beginning compensation as a faculty member?
My beginning compensation as a faculty member at a 12-month basis was $5,200, and it was the highest paid assistant professor in the university at that time.
And compared to other institutions and their salaries, how did that compare?
As far as you knew.
As far as my salary was concerned, it was pretty favorable because although as an instructor, I came out of a $4,800 salary.
And you, when you came back, you were a member of, describe the department that you... All right, there were two departments at that particular point in time.
See, in 1947,
The Department of... See, I came here in the fall of 1946 as a graduate student in animal nutrition.

In September 1947, the Department of Biochemistry and Nutrition was created, and I transferred so that my master's degree is in biochemistry and nutrition, one of the first three that was given, as far as Texas A&M is concerned.
So you came back to that department.
Well, so I, then I was in that department, and so I knew the department.
It had about eight faculty people, and they had about eight faculty people when I returned in 1951. Who was the department head?
Carl Lyman.
Please describe him.
Make believe I didn't know him or anything about him.
Describe him as... Carl Lyman is, uh, was a quiet person.
He had got a PhD at the University of Pittsburgh and had been involved in the isolation of pantothenic acid, which is one of the vitamins.
He worked basically in protein and protein metabolism and nutrition.
He was the department head.
And did he or someone else as you arrived give you any advice as a junior faculty member?
As a matter of fact, no.
I just went in it.
I guess that's not entirely true.
A close associate, extremely close associate, because I was in the same office with him, was J. Russell Couch.
And I listened to Russell, and he was a flying boy, Anthony.
He was this kind of a person that could get around.
And so in terms of getting grants and things of a sort, I particularly.
As far as you could tell at that point, were there some guidelines or rules that a young faculty member was expected to follow, whether the rules were written or not?
No.
No.
You see, I was in biochemistry.
And I had roots in Wisconsin and Cornell and research.
And science was, in other words, moving towards science.
This was it.
I was not a practical animal husbandman at that particular point, although I taught the courses in animal nutrition and did research in large animals.
I was hired.

essentially to work in an animal breeding project to determine whether or not there could be constituents in the blood or something, biochemical constituents that were related to growth and growth rates.
Where were you all quartered and what facilities?
We were animal industries building.

I was down below and then eventually I went up to the third, fourth floor with a laboratory on the fourth floor which they had put some air conditioning in for us and I had an office and shared an office with Jack, with John Mac Prescott and it was a small office.
When, when did you two share an office?
He came a year after I did.
Because he came from Wisconsin and he got his PhD at Wisconsin under Esmond Snell, but he had finished it at the University of Texas as Ed Snell had moved to the University of Texas.
And so he followed him down there, but the PhD was from the University of Wisconsin.

In terms of rules or guidelines, what I was thinking of, was it assumed that a faculty member would be on the job a certain number of hours a day and would be dressed in a certain professional manner?
Yes.
What time did you all normally get here?
We got in about 8 o'clock and stayed till 5, 6, 7.
We spent at least 40 hours a week, 45 hours.
We were often here in the evenings and doing research unless the temperature got too hot and things of this sort.
Occasionally we'd go to a movie and
because there was no air conditioning, of course, and the buildings could get warm.
But fundamentally, we were kind of critical of everybody else because they didn't stay the extra hours.
They didn't do the extra hours of research and things of that sort.
Well, the biochemistry here was new.
Who were the senior scholars in the department when you arrived?
Well, the ones I remember mostly, I missed one particularly, who was Ralph Holman.
Holman?
Holman.
H-O-L-M-A-N?
who came in during the period I was at graduate school at Cornell and post-doctorate at Wisconsin.
He went up to essentially back home to Minnesota and has been elected to the National Academy of Sciences there.
Raymond Reiser was always there.
Was he, was he present at that time?
He was present at that time, very much so.
Ray Richardson, L.R.
Richardson.
Let's digress.
Raymond College.
There were about five or six faculty members, and we called it this, what,
Seven Little Kingdoms, because we were totally independent of each other, with Mac Prescott, of course, being one of the things.
We were totally independent of each other.
We'd help with each other.
Our graduate students, faculty would sometimes jump all over the place and jump on them.
And particularly, they made presentations of seminars and things of the sort.
Seminars used to be on Saturday mornings.
Did you seven though get together in any professional manner during the day or during the week?
No.
No, we...
Didn't eat lunch together, didn't go to coffee together.
We didn't eat lunch together.
Because we were a small enough group, we always... And that seminar was appointed, which we generally all accumulated together.
Let's digress on Raymond Reiser.
When I got here, he...
I soon realized he was kind of the self-appointed leader of the Jewish community here.
Was...
Were there many Jewish faculty members or staff members?
I really don't know.
I don't think so, but I don't know.
All right, back to the mainstream.
Did you have any teaching duties that first year?
Yes, I taught animal nutrition.
Is that a...
Animal science or animal husbandry, 303.
Animal nutrition.
Just about all animal science majors took it?
Everybody in agriculture took it.
How large were the sections in the early years?
Oh, the largest section I think I had was 165.
Describe teaching that course.
What was it like?
It was fun.
It was in the auditorium at the, what they call AI building, animal industries building.
and they could go down and they eventually had one of these roll situations that you could do with a projection hub to keep.
Apparently I sold myself very well because within four years
I was named by the Agricultural Council as the outstanding faculty.
That's great.
And then in 1956, five years after I was here, I got the first of the
Farmer Students Award for teaching.
Did you get one the first year they were given?
No, I got it the second year they were given, which is all right with me because the stipend was only $500 the first year, and it was $1,000 the next year.
As a teacher, what were your guidelines that you had for yourself about teaching?
My guidelines, I guess, for myself, I'm not even sure I really understood them.
But you must have had some principles.
I had some principles, but the only teaching experience I had is I took a course in methods of teaching in the Army.
And I used those, and I came in and used those.
And I got to the point where I didn't...
I didn't use any notes.
I walked in and started lecturing.
Did the students think it was a tough course or an easy course?
The students thought it was a tough course.
Did they have a nickname for it?
Uncle Kunkel's Mystery Hour.
Uncle Kunkel.
So was your nickname Uncle Kunkel?
Uncle Kunkel, yeah.
And so that was known, at least later on, it was known as Uncle Kunkel's Mystery Hour.
But you didn't grade on the curve.
You did grade on it?
Oh, sure.
Oh, okay.
I did.
I always did.
And all animal science majors had to take it?
All agriculture majors.
All ag majors.
Oh, okay.
Okay.
Do you remember any pranks or jokes the students attempted to play on Uncle Kunkel?
Oh, not particularly.
walked in one day and one student was writing Uncle Kunkel's Mystery Hour on the blackboard.
He looked up and saw me.
Then he took off and it seemed for the rest of the class.
But I didn't mind it.
You checked the roll.
I checked the roll.
Oh, you bet.
Attendance was important as far as I was concerned.
It's always important as long as I taught.
And it had a, did it have a lab?
No.
Oh, it was all lecture.
All lecture.
How many years did you teach it?
11 years.
And did you enjoy the teaching part?
Yes, I did.
Because I would have been surprised if you had said no.
I actually taught three other courses.
What were they?
I taught enzymes in, or at least half the course of enzymes with Carl Lyman.
in biochemistry.

I taught because, you know, my major professor had won the Nobel Prize because of the isolation of urease, which essentially gave the structure as far as enzymology was concerned, enzymes was concerned.
I taught, of course, in large animal nutrition.
which I drew heavily from the physiology that I had had at Cornell.
And then I took a course called biochemical genetics.
And it was essentially the first molecular genetics or molecular biology course ever taught at Texas A&M.
I taught that about the second year that I was there.
It was in plant science department.
So I was teaching in animal husbandry, biochemistry, and plant sciences.
